{"ts":"2026-06-27T05:08:40.204Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Checking Import Statements**\n\nI'm making good progress! I've confirmed the beautiful structure of `WorkspaceCard`, `MetricTile`, and `StatusBadge`. Now, I'm shifting focus to importing these components correctly into the new `app/portal/governance/page.tsx` page. Before I proceed, I'm double-checking the existing content of that file to ensure proper integration.\n\n\n**Designing Filter Options**\n\nI'm now focusing on designing the filter options for the governance workspace. I've compiled lists for projects, agents, status, and severity. I'm thinking about how these filters interact. Now, I understand any combination of filters affects all data lists, not just one. This will be the next challenge for the interface.\n\n\n**Verifying Data Structure**\n\nI've gotten a really cool idea! If a user picks a specific project like \"Sovereign Core Sandbox 02,\" I need to show *only* the policies, oversight points, and documents connected to that project. Thankfully, my initial check indicates items contain `projectId`, `agentId`, `status`, and `severity` fields. I'm now making sure all data is structured correctly in the code for the policy guardrails, AI operation checks, and human oversight points to make this filtering a reality.\n\n\n**Defining Data Structure**\n\nI've got a great data model for governance documentation now. I have clarified the fields for severity, project, and agent details, along with request information and a description. I'm focusing now on the document structure itself: unique IDs, names, sizes, formats, upload dates, categories, clearance levels, statuses, and severities, all linked to projects and agents.\n\nI'm now implementing this into a powerful filtering function in React, and making sure the data structures are aligned for filtering.\n\n\n**Designing Layout and Components**\n\nI've just landed on a solid filtering